Recommended Cleanup
Use tap-hold-press for everything? Not necessarily. But for home-row mods, tap-hold-release is usually the gold standard. However, we can use the defalias shorthand to keep it from looking like "alphabet soup."

Simplified deflayer alignment: Using _ (transparent) and XX (none) effectively keeps your layers visually mapped to your physical keyboard.

Spacebar efficiency: Your spc_nav is currently using a 150ms tap time. I've standardized that to your variables for easier global tweaking.

The "Cleaned" Config
Lisp
(defcfg
  process-unmapped-keys yes
)

(defsrc
  u i o
  a s d f   h j k l ;
  m , .
  lalt caps rsft spc
)

;; Variables make it easy to tune the "feel" without hunting through aliases
(defvar
  tap-time 200
  hold-time 200
)

(defalias
  ;; Use the shorthand variables to keep the alias block readable
  ;; Home-row mods: tap-hold-release is best for avoiding accidental triggers while typing fast
  ctl_a (tap-hold-release $tap-time $hold-time a lctl)
  alt_s (tap-hold-release $tap-time $hold-time s lalt)
  met_d (tap-hold-release $tap-time $hold-time d lmet)
  sft_f (tap-hold-release $tap-time $hold-time f lsft)

  sft_j (tap-hold-release $tap-time $hold-time j rsft)
  met_k (tap-hold-release $tap-time $hold-time k rmet)
  alt_l (tap-hold-release $tap-time $hold-time l ralt)
  ctl_sc (tap-hold-release $tap-time $hold-time ; rctl)

  ;; Functional Aliases
  nav (tap-hold-press $tap-time $hold-time spc (layer-toggle nav-layer))
  a_esc (tap-hold $tap-time $hold-time esc lalt)
  s_cap (tap-hold $tap-time $hold-time caps rsft)
)

(deflayer default
  u         i         o
  @ctl_a    @alt_s    @met_d    @sft_f     h    @sft_j    @met_k    @alt_l    @ctl_sc
  m         ,         .
  @a_esc    bspc      @s_cap    @nav
)

(deflayer nav-layer
  pgup      up        pgdn
  _         _         _         _          bspc left      down      right     del
  home      _         end
  _         _         _         _
)
Key Improvements Explained
Variable Consistency: I applied your $tap-time and $hold-time variables to your alt_esc and rsft_caps aliases. Previously, those had hard-coded 150 values. Keeping them consistent prevents that "weird jittery feeling" when switching between different keys.

Visual Spacing: I adjusted the spacing in the deflayer blocks. In Kanata, whitespace is free—aligning your keys vertically makes it much easier to spot errors in your mapping at a glance.

Alias Naming: Shortened spc_nav to @nav and alt_esc to @a_esc. It’s purely aesthetic, but it keeps the deflayer block from getting too wide.

